197
00:25:23,573 --> 00:25:24,500
Hey Jiro.

198
00:25:24,520 --> 00:25:25,447
Ready?

199
00:25:28,068 --> 00:25:31,211
All the new buildings are old-fashioned.

200
00:25:31,655 --> 00:25:33,464
The streets are wider.

201
00:25:33,573 --> 00:25:35,841
Even the airplanes haven't changed.

202
00:25:37,994 --> 00:25:39,470
Welcome!

203
00:25:44,251 --> 00:25:46,018
Mackerel again?

204
00:25:46,127 --> 00:25:47,644
It's great.

205
00:25:47,681 --> 00:25:49,149
Every day's the same.

206
00:25:49,169 --> 00:25:50,637
Same lunch, same lectures.

207
00:25:50,674 --> 00:25:52,816
Can I get an egg?

208
00:25:53,426 --> 00:25:56,153
The Western powers are building all-metal aircraft.

209
00:25:57,013 --> 00:25:58,781
Try the pork sometime.

210
00:25:59,182 --> 00:26:01,784
We're more than ten years behind.

211
00:26:02,852 --> 00:26:04,161
What?

212
00:26:04,354 --> 00:26:05,704
Beautiful, isn't it?

213
00:26:06,481 --> 00:26:08,665
Look at that wonderful curve.

214
00:26:08,692 --> 00:26:11,710
You eat mackerel to look at the bones?

215
00:26:12,205 --> 00:26:13,757
Come on, finish up.

216
00:26:13,777 --> 00:26:15,329
We're going for coffee.

217
00:26:27,210 --> 00:26:29,520
Jiro sure is working hard.

218
00:26:29,629 --> 00:26:31,355
Fish bones.

219
00:26:31,808 --> 00:26:32,922
Is Mr.

220
00:26:32,942 --> 00:26:34,056
Horikoshi back from lunch?

221
00:26:34,175 --> 00:26:35,234
Jiro!

222
00:26:35,468 --> 00:26:37,653
Honjo, listen to this.

223
00:26:37,887 --> 00:26:42,032
The NACA has a standard curve just like this bone.

224
00:26:42,142 --> 00:26:43,867
Do Americans eat mackerel too?

225
00:26:43,893 --> 00:26:46,161
Jiro, package for you.

226
00:26:47,063 --> 00:26:50,999
A lady brought this for you, sir.

227
00:26:51,026 --> 00:26:53,419
You were out, so she left it with me.

228
00:26:53,496 --> 00:26:54,756
I see.

229
00:26:54,776 --> 00:26:56,036
Thank you.

230
00:26:57,574 --> 00:27:00,217
Present from your sweetheart?

231
00:27:00,337 --> 00:27:01,763
Got a smoke?

232
00:27:01,783 --> 00:27:03,209
Gimme one.

233
00:27:19,731 --> 00:27:20,678
- Jiro!

234
00:27:20,698 --> 00:27:21,645
- Let him go.

235
00:27:46,132 --> 00:27:46,896
- Hello, Mr.

236
00:27:46,916 --> 00:27:47,680
Horikoshi.

237
00:27:47,700 --> 00:27:48,464
- Back from school.

238
00:27:48,635 --> 00:27:50,687
Your guest is waiting.

239
00:27:50,707 --> 00:27:52,759
A young lady.

240
00:27:52,796 --> 00:27:54,605
Oh, right.

241
00:28:03,973 --> 00:28:05,657
Honestly, where were you?

242
00:28:06,309 --> 00:28:08,160
Kayo, I'm sorry.

243
00:28:08,895 --> 00:28:10,412
I completely forgot.

244
00:28:10,480 --> 00:28:11,788
Really!

245
00:28:12,117 --> 00:28:13,293
- Where's Mother?

246
00:28:13,313 --> 00:28:14,489
- At Uncle's.

247
00:28:14,619 --> 00:28:15,879
- Is she staying there?

248
00:28:15,899 --> 00:28:17,159
- Just for one night.

249
00:28:17,997 --> 00:28:19,945
You've grown, Kayo.

250
00:28:19,965 --> 00:28:21,913
And gotten very pretty, too.

251
00:28:22,001 --> 00:28:24,200
You're so mean.

252
00:28:24,220 --> 00:28:26,419
You never ever come home.

253
00:28:29,833 --> 00:28:32,768
Oh, it's almost sunset already.

254
00:28:32,846 --> 00:28:35,065
I'll tell them I kept you.

255
00:28:35,085 --> 00:28:37,304
Let's take the penny steamer.

256
00:28:39,467 --> 00:28:42,027
She must really like you.

257
00:28:42,137 --> 00:28:44,821
Come on, it's been two years.

258
00:28:44,931 --> 00:28:47,658
Didn't you try to see her again?

259
00:28:47,694 --> 00:28:49,017
Of course.

260
00:28:49,037 --> 00:28:50,360
I went back once.

261
00:29:02,282 --> 00:29:05,175
The fire stopped at her street.

262
00:29:05,378 --> 00:29:06,054
See?

263
00:29:06,074 --> 00:29:06,750
There's the dock.

264
00:29:19,966 --> 00:29:21,191
Are you cold?

265
00:29:21,227 --> 00:29:23,301
I'm fine.

266
00:29:23,321 --> 00:29:25,395
I never dreamed Tokyo would recover so quickly.

267
00:29:29,726 --> 00:29:32,369
Can I stay with you, Jiro?

268
00:29:32,812 --> 00:29:35,747
Father won't let me live here by myself.

269
00:29:35,857 --> 00:29:39,751
I'll probably be in Nagoya by the time you come.

270
00:29:39,871 --> 00:29:40,881
- With an airplane company?

271
00:29:40,901 --> 00:29:41,911
- Yes.

272
00:29:42,197 --> 00:29:43,922
Men have it so good.

273
00:29:44,157 --> 00:29:47,676
I want to study medicine in Tokyo.

274
00:29:48,046 --> 00:29:49,597
A doctor?

275
00:29:49,617 --> 00:29:51,168
I think you might be a good one.

276
00:29:51,414 --> 00:29:53,181
I think so too.

277
00:29:53,249 --> 00:29:56,059
I'll talk to Father next time I'm home.

278
00:29:56,179 --> 00:29:57,355
Thanks.

279
00:29:57,375 --> 00:29:58,551
I'm counting on you.

280
00:31:04,737 --> 00:31:05,962
Jiro!

281
00:31:08,324 --> 00:31:09,633
There you are.

282
00:31:09,669 --> 00:31:10,407
- You made it.

283
00:31:10,427 --> 00:31:11,165
- Finally.

284
00:31:11,296 --> 00:31:12,556
- We're on our way.

285
00:31:12,576 --> 00:31:13,836
- Yes, we are.

286
00:31:32,181 --> 00:31:35,492
They must've been heading for the city.

287
00:31:35,518 --> 00:31:37,160
There were hundreds of them.

288
00:31:37,186 --> 00:31:39,287
There's no work in the countryside.

289
00:31:43,703 --> 00:31:45,359
Another bank failure.

290
00:31:45,379 --> 00:31:47,035
Which one is it this time?

